  "instructions": {
    "L": [
      {
        "S": "Rinse 1 cup red lentils in a fine-mesh sieve under cold running water until the water runs clear to remove surface starch and prevent excessive foaming. Drain and set aside."
      },
      {
        "S": "Heat 1 1/2 tablespoons coconut oil in a large pot or Dutch oven over medium heat. Add 1 finely diced small yellow onion and a pinch of salt once the oil is shimmering. Cook for 4 to 5 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the onion is translucent and beginning to turn golden. Add 4 cloves minced garlic and 1 tablespoon minced fresh ginger and cook for 1 minute, stirring constantly to prevent burning."
      },
      {
        "S": "Add 3/4 teaspoon sea salt, 1 teaspoon ground cumin, 1 teaspoon curry powder, 1/2 teaspoon ground coriander, 1/2 teaspoon ground turmeric, and 1/4 to 1/2 teaspoon chili powder. Stir well and cook for 30 to 60 seconds until very fragrant and the spices darken slightly. Add a splash of broth to deglaze if the spices begin to stick."
      },
      {
        "S": "Add 1 (14 ounce) can crushed tomatoes and stir well. Cook for 2 to 3 minutes, allowing the tomatoes to darken in color and concentrate. Add the rinsed lentils and 2 cups vegetable broth. Stir well, increase heat to high, and bring to a boil. Skim any foam that rises to the surface. Reduce heat to medium-low, partially cover the pot, and simmer for 18 to 22 minutes, stirring occasionally to prevent sticking, until the lentils are completely cooked through and have mostly broken down into a thick, creamy consistency."
      },
      {
        "S": "Shake the can well, then pour in 1 (14 ounce) can full-fat coconut milk and stir to combine. Add up to 1 cup of water if you prefer a thinner consistency. Simmer uncovered for 5 more minutes, stirring occasionally."
      },
      {
        "S": "Remove the pot from heat. Stir in 1 teaspoon garam masala, 2 tablespoons almond butter, and 1 1/2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice until fully incorporated. Taste and adjust seasoning with more salt, additional lemon juice for brightness, a pinch of sugar to balance acidity, or more chili for heat. Note that the curry will thicken as it sits."
      },
      {
        "S": "Heat 1 tablespoon coconut oil in a small skillet over medium-high heat for an optional tadka. Add 1 teaspoon cumin seeds or mustard seeds and cook until they begin to sputter and pop, about 30 seconds. Add 2 cloves thinly sliced garlic and a pinch of crushed red pepper flakes and cook for 15 to 20 seconds until garlic is just golden. Pour the sizzling tadka immediately over the curry and stir gently."
      },
      {
        "S": "Ladle the curry into bowls over 4 cups hot cooked basmati rice, about 1 cup per serving, or alongside warm naan bread or flatbread. Garnish generously with fresh cilantro and serve with lemon wedges on the side."
      }
    ]
  },
  "notes": {
    "L": [
      {
        "S": "Gluten-Free: This recipe is naturally gluten-free as written. Verify that vegetable broth and curry powder are certified gluten-free. If serving with naan, use gluten-free naan."
      },
      {
        "S": "Nut Allergy: The almond butter adds creaminess and body. For nut-free versions, substitute with sunflower seed butter, tahini, or simply omit."
      },
      {
        "S": "Dairy-Free and Vegan: This recipe is naturally vegan and dairy-free as written."
      },
      {
        "S": "Lentil Type: Red lentils or split red lentils (masoor dal) work best as they break down into a creamy consistency. Do not substitute brown, green, or French lentils."
      },
      {
        "S": "Coconut Milk: Full-fat coconut milk is essential for the ultra-creamy texture. Shake the can vigorously before opening. Light coconut milk will work but yields a thinner result."
      },
      {
        "S": "Make it Heartier: Stir in 2 to 3 handfuls of baby spinach or chopped kale during step 5 for added nutrition and color."
      },
      {
        "S": "Scaling: This recipe doubles beautifully. Increase simmer time by 5 minutes for a double batch."
      },
      {
        "S": "Storage: Refrigerate leftovers in an airtight container for up to 5 days, or freeze for up to 3 months. Thin with water or broth when reheating as the curry thickens when cold. Reheat gently over medium-low heat, stirring frequently."
      }
    ]
  },
